@akien-mga this does not work on C++17, atleast for MSVC:
```
	XrEventDataBuffer runtimeEvent = {
		.type = XR_TYPE_EVENT_DATA_BUFFER,
		.next = nullptr
	};
```

And even on C++20 MSVC has small syntax differences compared to LLVM and MSVC requires you to keep the fields in the order of the struct, while on other compilers you can reorder them. On both though you can leave fields out and they will be zero filled.

That said, this syntax is far more readable and far easier to understand than the C++17 syntax I'm currently using (though the comments help in accomplishing the same :))

I think in C++17 you can do:
```
XrEventDataBuffer runtimeEvent = {};
// or XrEventDataBuffer runtimeEvent{};
runtimeEvent.type = XR_TYPE_EVENT_DATA_BUFFER;
```
The init with `{}` should zero everything in the struct and then you can set the members you care about outside the init.

Tested, works as early as C++11:
```cpp
#include <iostream>

class SomeClass {
public:
	int class_a = 5;
	SomeClass() {}
};

struct SomeStruct {
	int some_int;
	float some_float;
	SomeClass some_obj;
	SomeClass *some_ptr;
};

int main() {
	SomeStruct some_str = {};
	std::cout << some_str.some_int << " " << some_str.some_float << " " << some_str.some_obj.class_a << " " << some_str.some_ptr << std::endl;
	SomeStruct other_str;
	std::cout << other_str.some_int << " " << other_str.some_float << " " << other_str.some_obj.class_a << " " << other_str.some_ptr << std::endl;
	return 0;
}
```
```
$ g++ -std=c++11 test.cpp
$ ./a.out
0 0 5 0
-327758120 4.55576e-41 5 0x7effec76d160
```

Both `SomeStruct some_str{};` and `SomeStruct some_str = {};` are valid and more or less equivalent. Last we discussed it we opted for using the latter as we found it more readable / clearer that it's an initialization.

